answers.body_markdown:
Unlike in C, a Java String is not suitable for holding bytes.  Converting bytes to a String [decodes](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/charset/CharsetDecoder.html) the bytes, which means some values may be altered or lost.

Even if no values were altered, your data is not going to represent characters, so printing it as text will display nonsense.  For instance, many of your bytes are zero, which does not show at all in output, since character `\u0000` is a non-printing control character.

You should avoid Strings and StringBuilders entirely.  Instead, store your bytes in the byte array only:

    while (totalBytesRead &lt; length) {
        int currentBytesRead = in.read(messageByte,
            totalBytesRead, length - totalBytesRead);
        totalBytesRead = currentBytesRead + totalBytesRead;
    }

Your data appears to consist entirely of `short` values, so, assuming the C client is built to regard `short` as a 16-bit value, and assuming the C compiler didn’t pad your `struct` members in order to word-align them, you can convert your bytes to a sequence of shorts using [ByteBuffer](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/ByteBuffer.html) and [ShortBuffer](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/nio/ShortBuffer.html):

    ByteBuffer buffer = ByteBuffer.wrap(messageByte);
    ShortBuffer shortBuffer = buffer.asShortBuffer();

To print them, retrieve them as an array and use [Arrays.toString](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/13/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Arrays.html#toString%28short[]%29):

    short[] values = new short[length / 2];
    shortBuffer.get(values);
    System.out.println(Arrays.toString(values));

